Micromorphology of pollen grain:
—The pollen grains is large (50–100 µm in diameter), isopolar, 3-colpate, oblate spheroidal, polar area is small, subtriangular and subcircular amb, long colpi, widest colpi (ca. 3.6 µm wide), sexine less thick, exine microechinate, perforate with annular perforations conspicuous (
Fig. 2
). Palynological evidence shows the separation of pollen grains from the nearest species, mainly in the pollen variables of equatorial diameter, polar view equatorial diameter, length, and width of the bodies; however, they are similar to the number of apertures, presenting three (

Gonzaga 
et al
. 2019

) and morphometric analyses using vegetative and reproductive flower variables (
Gonzaga 2020
).
